version_unique_justification: We use semantic versioning for this project. The version number is exposed with cmake and with git tags.
release_notes_vulns_justification: No vulnerability has been found in this library. Most of the code is in the form of a template, and if there is any vulnerability is caused by compiling a particular, valid instantiation, we will respond and fix the bug.
report_tracker_justification:
The GitHub issue tracker tracks individual issues.

https://github.com/gracicot/kangaru/issues
report_process_justification:
The GitHub interface permit any user to report bugs.

https://github.com/gracicot/kangaru/issues
build_floss_tools_justification: This library support building using GCC and Clang
test_justification: All our test are publicly available at this URL: https://github.com/gracicot/kangaru/tree/master/test/src All of them are run automatically on travis: https://travis-ci.org/gracicot/kangaru and appveyor: https://ci.appveyor.com/project/gracicot/kangaru
test_invocation_justification: The command `ctest` will run all tests and report a summary
test_most_justification: How code is mostly templates. There is only a few runtime branches and they are tested in multiple instantiation context.
test_policy_justification: In our contributing guideline, we suggest adding tests when a functionality would benefit from it.
tests_are_added_justification: All major improvements have tests added for it in all versions that had automatic testing.
warnings_justification: Our examples and tests are compiled with warnings enabled.
warnings_fixed_justification: Warnings are considered an issue that need to be addressed. If a warning is deemed useful and informative, we will commit to support this warning.
warnings_strict_justification: We are using -Wall and -Wextra on GCC and Clang. We are enabling /W3 on msvc.
know_secure_design_justification: One primary developer, Guillaume Racicot, passed a security course at Ã‰TS MontrÃ©al.
crypto_published_justification: No network communication is done in this library
crypto_call_justification: We do not use any communication between computers or other processes.
delivery_mitm_justification: Github is using HTTPS and SSH to deliver downloads and clones
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: We commit to fix any major security issues within acceptable times and backport the fix on supported versions.
static_analysis_justification: We are using bettercodehub: https://bettercodehub.com/results/gracicot/kangaru codacy: https://app.codacy.com/project/gracicot/kangaru/dashboard and lgtm: https://lgtm.com/projects/g/gracicot/kangaru/
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: Both lgtm and codacy are using many guideline and diagnostic on how to fix security related issues and how to adopt a better style.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Inputs to this library are user class. Compile time fuzzing and concept fuzzing is a very complicated subject that hasn't been explored a lot in the industry. No standard tools that help with our issue have been found yet.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: A memory analyzer should run our tests on every supported platform. The integration with our build tools hasn't been done yet.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: If any of our users find a vulnerability using such tool, we commit to address the issue as fast as possible. Upon integration of dynamic analysis, we will check every commit for issues.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: No password or any keys are registered inside the repository or documentation
english_justification: Our documentation, both contained in the project repository and the GitHub wiki is in English, and the issue process is in English too.

warnings_justification: No compiled languages are used by CAIRIS. 'use strict' is set on all JavaScript modules.

warnings_strict_justification: It is our policy to address warnings when they are flagged during automated testing.  We are proactive in findings these when they arise due to incompatibility issues, and run our automated tests on both Python 2 and Python 3.
know_secure_design_justification: The primary maintainer has a PhD in Computer Science cogent to computer security, and lectures / carries out research in Security by Design: http://staffprofiles.bournemouth.ac.uk/display/sfaily

crypto_published_justification: CAIRIS relies on flask security for supporting processes and data for authentication, including cryptography.  CAIRIS doesn't currently employ cryptography at rest or in transit in any other context, but this is currently under review.
crypto_call_justification: CAIRIS relies on flask security for supporting processes and data for authentication, including cryptography.  CAIRIS doesn't currently employ cryptography at rest or in transit in any other context, but this is currently under review.
crypto_floss_justification: CAIRIS uses flask_security, which uses FLOSS libraries only.
crypto_keylength_justification: CAIRIS relies on flask security for supporting processes and data for authentication, including cryptography.  CAIRIS doesn't currently employ cryptography at rest or in transit in any other context, but this is currently under review.
crypto_working_justification: CAIRIS relies on flask security for supporting processes and data for authentication, including cryptography.  CAIRIS doesn't currently employ cryptography at rest or in transit in any other context, but this is currently under review.
crypto_pfs_justification: CAIRIS relies on flask security for supporting processes and data for authentication, including protection against CSRF attacks.  CAIRIS doesn't currently employ cryptography at rest or in transit in any other context, but this is currently under review.
crypto_password_storage_justification: CAIRIS user account passwords are hashed and salted when first used.
crypto_random_justification: We follow practices prescribed by flask security when initialising flask security components.
delivery_mitm_justification: MITMs can be addressed in a number of ways.  If CAIRIS is hosted on a domain where only https traffic is allowed then traffic to/from the CAIRIS is sent over http.  Alternatively, mod_wsgi-express to run over TLS, but configuration of mod_wsgi-express is not within the scope of CAIRIS.
delivery_unsigned_justification: No hashes are retrieved over the network.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: No publicly known CAIRIS vulnerabilities have been reported.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: No publicly known CAIRIS vulnerabilities have been reported.

sites_password_security_justification: No authentication needed for external users.

crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: Not OK for symmetric-key algorithms. For public key primitives, the choice is often non-existent: trapdoor permutation can (almost) only be instantiated with RSA, concise puncturable encryption with bilinear maps.
